node.text:
4 DAYS UNTIL SELFHEALERS CIRCLE ENROLLMENT 🎉

Thanks to member feedback, we’ve spent the past year building our own hosting platform. It’s easier to navigate + we now have a private community outside of facebook. Members are loving our new space.

The cost is $26/month or $286/year (one month free). My goal has always been to make the Circle affordable + accessible.

Enrollment will open January 1st at 12pm PST. Spaces are limited + do SELL OUT quickly. If you’re on the waitlist, you’ll be sent a link a few moments before enrollment opens. It might be helpful to set an alarm. There are currently 30,000+ people on the waitlist.

To find complete details on what the circle is all about, click the link in my bio. You can also add yourself to the waitlist.

I’ll see you in the ⭕️ + cannot wait for your healing journey to begin! selfhealers

node.text: Today it’s a true honor to talk to @dr.editheger— I’m actually a bit overwhelmed post filming this. Edith is a psychologist + Holocaust survivor who just released the book “The Gift.” I got chills throughout the book + know members of this community will love every word. Edith is an embodied teacher who gifts us with the wisdom that we are not not victims of our past, but powerful creators of our future. Her story is a testament to our true human potential. She’s a gift. I hope you all enjoy #selfhealers

node.text:
Outrage culture sells. And it’s selling in a big way right now.

This is because it’s addictive. 

The hormonal responses in the body + the pull of our ego to feel superior is seductive. Every day can become an emotional roller coaster where we feel more + more angry + less able to focus our energy on things that serve us. At the same time it is also the only time we actually *feel* which can make us come back for more + more because the fleeting emotions of outrage feel better than feeling nothing at all.

When we exist within outrage culture, we exist in survival mode. The primitive “lizard” part of our brain is dominate which leads to knee-jerk reactions, impulsivity, + self neglect.

The physical/mental affects are: brain fog fatigue, inability to think logically, indecisiveness, memory issues, + high emotional reactivity (or complete shut down.)

To heal, we must become conscious to what we consume, how we behave, + face the reality of what our beliefs do for our own ego. This takes a lot of radical honesty.

As we heal we have more access to our pre-frontal cortex. The part of our brain that allows for creativity, solutions, rational thinking, connection, collaboration.

In short: we leave the righteous ego self (survival mode) for the self that is able to make impact + create meaningful change.

We also become more confident, more in control of our emotional states, + more empathetic tolerate to ideas beyond our limited perspective.

Do you notice outrage culture in your life? #selfhealers

node.text:
I spent a large majority of my life completely unaware of my needs. My childhood conditioning was to focus on everyone else— everyone else’s feelings, everyone else’s emotions. 

I was conditioned to be polite, to achieve, + to people please.

Where there’s people pleasing, there is betrayal of our own needs.

The path to healing involves becoming conscious to our needs.

Here’s some real life examples of how I practiced from this past week.

1. I’m tired and don’t want to record videos planned for that day. 

Meeting my need: acknowledge I’m tired without self shaming. Pause take a quick walk. Decide to cut filming in half and do the rest when my mindbody is recharged. Went to bed at 7pm judgment free.

2. Feeling grief sadness that this year my mom won’t call me on my upcoming birthday 

Meeting my need: share it with my partners who console me by simply listening. I cry. I sit in the stillness. I breathe. I watch grief come, then I watch it go.

3. I’m feeling needy + unloved (a theme my inner child revisits often)

Meeting my need: I express this. I annoy myself by expressing it. I pity myself for a little bit. I watch how placing expectations causes my own suffering. I forgive myself— or try to. I see this is a pattern. I see the pattern without judgement.

How do you practice meeting your needs OR, do you struggle to understand what they are? #selfhealers

node.text:
Trauma bonds are seen as “normal” in our culture. Sometimes, they’re even romanticized. Unpredictability is seen as mystery. On + off dynamics make entire tv series. Performing or measuring up to be chosen is the basis of one of the longest running reality shows.

It’s no surprise when we understand that childhood attachments (the relationships we have with parent figures who we depend on for survival) are often unpredictable , unsafe, chaotic, abusive, or have emotional neglect. 

When this happens, we still seek this love. We need it. So, we internalize the belief that something must be “wrong with us.” This is the start of betraying ourselves + parts of who we are to gain love or approval.

This same pattern occurs in trauma bonds.

The beautiful part of trauma bonds is that they can be healed. We can learn so much about our family system dynamics in the process. We can learn to trust ourselves, to hold boundaries, to communicate clearly, to find safety in our bodies.

We can all heal. We can all unlearn #selfhealers

node.text:
To understand yourself, it’s important to understand the subconscious mind.

The subconscious mind means sub (below) consciousness. It’s what we are not conscious to. It stores all of our memories, beliefs, experiences— many that we cannot even consciously remember. 

Our subconscious mind has something called a homeostatic impulse. This is the subconscious mind keeping us thinking the same thoughts + behaviors. It keeps us living in the same patterns.

For many of us, life has been filled with struggle, lack, chaos, emotional abandonment. This is what we knew in the most important years of our lives (age birth-7).

So when we start healing, when we start making choice in alignment with who we truly are— the subconscious mind goes off like an alarm “what’s this!” “Nooo... this is different” “I’m not deserving of this.” And countless other fear based thoughts come from the mind.

After the thoughts, come the emotions. After the emotions come behaviors. These behaviors are typically self sabotaging behaviors— pushing someone away, being late for that job interview, not following through, falling into negative habits/addictions. 

What this actually is is the subconscious mind keeping us safe. For the subconscious mind the predictable is safe, even if the predictable is misery.

When you begin your healing journey, there will be many moments this happens. And that’s ok— just witness it. Just see it. Just notice yourself being pulled into those familiar patterns. 

Then forgive + choose again.

Then forgive + choose again #selfhealers

node.text:
Our egos are most fragile (meaning active) with close or romantic relationships.

The ego steps in to protect. That’s its job— to make sure we never feel the pain, shame, rejection, or abandonment of our past.

At the same time the unguided ego also makes connection difficult. Where there’s defensiveness + control there cannot be relationships of freedom, authenticity, + mutual evolution.

Our authentic self seeks freedom. We seek someone to truly know us, see us, hear us, + cherish us. We seek a partner who trusts themselves enough to trust us. And who sees us as not our wounded parts, but as the empowered, expensive self we all have  within. 

The authentic self says: “im feeling insecure, can you tell me how you feel about me?” It says: “that scared me I felt like you were abandoning us” It says: “I really want to have this conversation, I know it will be difficult but you mean so much to me + this matters.”

Ego says “ugh, you always do this.” “You never consider me.” “Why can’t you be more like (insert person)!” “I don’t need you anyway.”

Leave the ego consciousness for vulnerability + curiosity + watch your relationships change #selfhealers

node.text:
Many of us learned that love was conditional. We had to work for it since we were children.

Many of us had to perform, to prove we were ‘good,’ or we had to completely deny our own emotions in order to cope with our environment.

We learned that love or approval could leave at any moment.

So, we learned to state our case. To over explain. To over apologize.

We learned to rationalize our ‘why’ + attempt to make another person see our side of things because at our core we are afraid. Afraid of being abandoned.

I often find myself over-explaining or wanting to over explain myself. I witness my mind coming up with dozens of reasons to support my “case” when I set a boundary. I witness myself reading a comment about me or my work online + I see my mind desperate to defend the truth as I see it.

I see my inner child afraid that not good enough. This is when we default to defense + explanation.

This is the best time to practice.

The truth is we do not need to defend our worth. We do not need to defend our truth. We do not need to apologize for our limits, our needs, our ambition, or dreams, or our desires— even when it brings up insecurities in those around us.

With healing, with developed self-trust + confidence comes less explaining + more BEING. Sovereign being.

Some reminders when you feel the urge to over-explain:
1. Boundaries are your right. People who guilt or shame you for your boundaries are struggling with their own abandonment wounding

2. Your reality + truth is always valid— simply because you’ve experienced it

3. People project their own sense of self + unresolved pain onto others (this is part of the human experience) personalizing this pain is a choice that can be un-learned

4. People with high self worth respect the needs of others— because they respect their own needs 

5. Inner child wounding can create a scenario where 2 adults become children: practice self forgiveness + grace #selfhealers

node.text:
Many of us are living each day reacting to our own emotional states. This causes reactive behaviors that we later regret or feel shame around. 

We are not our emotions— we experience emotions. 

But for most of us, our reaction to our emotions drive our behavior. And, that behavior can keep us in cycles + patterns that no longer serve us.

We can all do the work to become conscious neutral witnesses to our emotions. When we do this, we observe how the emotions impact our mind + body without becoming the emotion or letting the emotion pull us into unconscious knee-jerk reactions.

True power comes from allowing any emotion to flow through the body. By watching it come + go. By seeing how in just 24 hours we can feel 10 different (usually conflicting emotions) about the same experience. 

This is how we learn emotions aren’t facts, they’re experiences. And they do not need to dictate our choices, behaviors, or reactions #selfhealers

What people truly want more than anything external is to be seen + loved for exactly who they are.

What people truly want is to be cherished, to be witnessed, to have someone they love see something that’s uniquely “them” + affirm that.

Many of us have been conditioned to compliment surface things: “I love your outfit,” “your hair looks amazing” “congrats on that new job” — + there is nothing wrong with that. 

If you want to see someone truly light up, speak words of love that shows them that you see them. Fully.

For many of you, this might feel awkward at first. Practice it. Affirm those around you. The more you do it, the more you’ll notice the beauty in everyone around you— even strangers.

The more you’ll notice the beauty in yourself.

We need more people who notice the beauty. Who notice the good. Who collaborate, who encourage, who lift up those around them as they lift themselves.

What has someone said to you that made you stop in your tracks + say: wow, they see me? #selfhealers

node.text:
Living a peaceful life is an act of intentional rebellion.

In our world filled with unresolved trauma outrage + chaos are full blown addictions. Most of us are stuck in this cycle every day + our nervous systems reflect that.

We have instant knee jerk reactions, we shut down, or we avoid so many experiences because we live within fear. Fear that if parts of our shadows were seen we wouldn’t be loved for who we actually are.

A pain from childhood that most of us have buried so deep we don’t even know it’s there.

Peace is a choice. We choose it each time we love ourselves enough to stop controlling the present moment.

Peace is a choice. We choose it every time we unconsciously are punishing or critiquing ourselves + consciously say— no, not today.

Peace is a choice. We choose it every time we humble ourselves to the truth that there are multiple realities + we don’t need to control how other people express their realities.

Peace is a choice. We choose it every time we hold our hand over our hearts, returning to the body + say I AM SAFE.

Peace is a choice. We choose it every time we witness our addiction to chaos with loving awareness + say I have a purpose, + I commit to letting it express through me #selfhealers
